Using multiple Condition objects with a ReentrantLock is one of the most powerful features of the java.util.concurrent package. It allows you to create specialized waiting rooms for different types of threads.
In a standard synchronized block, you only have one waiting room. If a producer finishes its work, it calls notifyAll(), which wakes up everyone—including other producers who might not be able to do anything yet. This causes "thread contention" and wastes CPU cycles.
With ReentrantLock and Condition, you can wake up only the threads that are actually ready to work.
The "Bounded Buffer" Example (Producer-Consumer)
Imagine a warehouse with limited space (a buffer).
 * Producers must wait if the warehouse is Full.
 * Consumers must wait if the warehouse is Empty.
import java.util.concurrent.locks.Condition;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.Lock;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock;

public class BoundedBuffer<T> {
    private final T[] items;
    private int putPtr, takePtr, count;

    private final Lock lock = new ReentrantLock();
    
    // Waiting room #1: For Producers waiting for space
    private final Condition notFull = lock.newCondition();
    
    // Waiting room #2: For Consumers waiting for items
    private final Condition notEmpty = lock.newCondition();

    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    public BoundedBuffer(int capacity) {
        items = (T[]) new Object[capacity];
    }

    public void put(T item) throws InterruptedException {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            // While the warehouse is full, producers wait in the 'notFull' room
            while (count == items.length) {
                notFull.await(); 
            }
            
            items[putPtr] = item;
            if (++putPtr == items.length) putPtr = 0;
            count++;

            // SUCCESS! We added an item. 
            // Signal ONLY the consumers (who are waiting in the 'notEmpty' room).
            notEmpty.signal(); 
            
        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }

    public T take() throws InterruptedException {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            // While the warehouse is empty, consumers wait in the 'notEmpty' room
            while (count == 0) {
                notEmpty.await();
            }

            T item = items[takePtr];
            if (++takePtr == items.length) takePtr = 0;
            count--;

            // SUCCESS! We removed an item and created space.
            // Signal ONLY the producers (who are waiting in the 'notFull' room).
            notFull.signal();
            
            return item;
        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }
}

Why this is a "Production-Grade" Pattern
 * Eliminates the "Thundering Herd": When a take() happens, we call notFull.signal(). This wakes up exactly one producer. In a synchronized version, notifyAll() would wake up every single producer and every other consumer, creating a massive spike in CPU usage as they all fight for the lock again.
 * Specific Signaling: You aren't just saying "Something changed!" You are saying "Specifically, there is now space available" or "Specifically, there is now an item to eat."
 * Efficiency with Virtual Threads: When a virtual thread calls await(), it is unmounted from the carrier thread. This allows you to have thousands of producers and consumers waiting "for free" without consuming OS resources.
Important Rules for Condition
 * Always use a while loop: Never use if with await(). This protects against "spurious wakeups" where a thread might wake up even if the condition hasn't been met.
 * Must hold the lock: You cannot call await() or signal() unless you have already called lock.lock(). If you don't, you'll get an IllegalMonitorStateException.
 * Finally block: Always unlock in a finally block to ensure the warehouse "door" isn't left locked forever if an error occurs.
